A theory of value for a tech startup designed to help restaurants reduce food waste could be grounded in leveraging data analytics, IoT (Internet of Things), and AI to optimize inventory and operations. The core value proposition revolves around cost savings, environmental sustainability, and operational efficiency.

 Value Creation;
The startup can develop a smart platform that integrates with restaurants' existing systems, such as point-of-sale (POS) devices and inventory management tools. Using IoT sensors, it could track real-time data on food usage, expiration dates, and inventory levels. AI algorithms would analyze this data to provide actionable insights, such as predicting demand, identifying surplus inventory, and recommending optimal purchasing schedules. 

Value Delivery;
The platformâ€™s user-friendly interface would deliver these insights through alerts and reports accessible via desktop or mobile devices. Partnerships with suppliers could also allow the platform to facilitate just-in-time deliveries, reducing overstocking. Moreover, the platform could suggest creative ways to repurpose surplus ingredients, minimizing waste.

Value Capture;
Revenue streams could include subscription fees, pay-per-use models, or commissions on partnerships with suppliers and food redistribution networks. Restaurants would benefit by cutting costs associated with wasted food, enhancing their brand reputation through sustainable practices, and potentially increasing customer loyalty.

This solution aligns with broader societal trends toward sustainability, making it a valuable proposition for restaurants striving to meet both economic and ethical goals.
